Housing Price Prediction¶

Nikhil N Barigidad

Predict Actual Value of the Prospective Properties

A US-based housing company named Surprise Housing has decided to enter the Australian market. The company uses data analytics to purchase houses at a price below their actual values and flip them on at a higher price

The company is looking at prospective properties to buy to enter the market. You are required to build a regression model using regularisation in order to predict the actual value of the prospective properties and decide whether to invest in them or not.

The company wants to know:

  • Which variables are significant in predicting the price of a house, and
  • How well those variables describe the price of a house.

#columns with same value repeated over 85% of the data will probably be skewed thus dropping such columns
colsTbD = []
num_cols = housingData.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64', 'object'])
for col in (num_cols):
    if(housingData[col].value_counts().max() > housingData.shape[0]*0.85):
        colsTbD.append(col)

housingData.drop(colsTbD, axis=1, inplace=True)

New columns¶

In [10]:
#Column to check whether the house is remodelled or not
def isRemodelled(row):
    if (row['YearBuilt'] == row['YearRemodAdd']):
        return 0
    elif (row['YearBuilt'] < row['YearRemodAdd']):
        return 1
    else:
        return 2

housingData['isRemodelled'] = housingData.apply(isRemodelled, axis=1)

#Lets find out age of the house remodelled
def remodelledAge(row):
    if(row['YearBuilt'] == row['YearRemodAdd']):
        return row['YrSold'] - row['YearBuilt']
    else:
        return row['YrSold'] - row['YearRemodAdd']
housingData['BuiltOrRemAge'] = housingData.apply(remodelledAge, axis=1)

#Oldest garage was built in 1900s and the newest is in 2010, 
#Garages built in and after 2000 will be consider as new and before 2000 will be old
#new=1, old=0

def newGarage(row):
    if(row['GarageYrBlt'] >= 2000):
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
housingData['newGarage'] = housingData.apply(newGarage, axis=1)

#Columns that only needs to be codes(i.e 1,2,3.. for the values)
objCol = list(housingData.select_dtypes(include='object').columns)

#columns that require to have seperate columns for all the unique values
objColTogetDummies = ['MSZoning', 'Neighborhood', 'GarageType', 'Fence', 'Exterior1st', 'Exterior2nd']
objColToCode = [x for x in objCol if x not in objColTogetDummies]
In [27]:
for col in objColToCode:
    housingData[col] = housingData[col].astype('category')

#_cd is abbreviation for coded columns 
for col in objColToCode:
    housingData[col+"_cd"] = housingData[col].cat.codes

plt.title('mean_score and alpha for lasso model')
plt.show()
  • r2_score for train data is highest at the left and keeps decresing there after whereas for test data it has small increase at the start and then goes on to decrease
  • The difference between r2_score for train and test data keeps decreasing as alpha increases, Thus the difference is minimal at the highest value of alpha i.e alpha=1000

Conclusion¶

The Optimal lambda($\lambda$) value for Ridge and Lasso are:

  • Ridge
    • $\lambda$ = 100, for all the features
    • $\lambda$ = 20, for the features selected using RFE
  • Lasso
    • $\lambda$ = 1000
  • The r2_score for Ridge with all the features is slightly ahead of the Ridge with top 50 features selected using RFE and also Lasso
  • Ridge with RFE(top 50) is giving out same accuracy as Lasso, Lasso is selecting 43 features in it's model
  • Top significant features in all the models are OverallQual, GrLivArea, TotalBsmtSF, GarageCars, BsmtFinSF1 and Neighborhood
